<dl id="n03124f"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n03" href="#n03124f">N03 (VI.B.3)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n03all.htm#n03124f"> 124(f)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> the fact remains <small>Blue</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n03124f"><li>FW 32.12 </li><li><a href="../../flex/b/lexb.htm#n03124f">2010</a> </li><li><a href="../../flex/b/l39b.htm#n03124f">1939</a> &nbsp;<a href="../../flex/z/lexfh.htm#n03124f">FH IX</a> </li><li><ms href="#n03124f">MS BL 47472-98</ms> </li><li>JJA 45:005 <a name="b11d" href="../../ff/fdra/bda.htm#b11d">Usage</a> </li><li> <a href="../../flex/b/b11d.htm#n03124f">Draft: I.2&sect;1.1</a></li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources">Granting that this is so, <mark>the fact still remains</mark> that there is much left unsaid by the poets. Some of them recognised the real significance of their love for nature when they told us how they were inspired by her to love, or were reminded of their lack of love. <small> Albert Mordell, <a name="AMEM" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#AMEM"><cite title="source">The Erotic Motive in Literature</cite></a> (1919) 164</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Note: RRJ: Joyce notices that Mordell is very fond of the words &ldquo;fact&rdquo; and &ldquo;it shows&rdquo;, especially when there are no facts, and nothing is shown. In between these two &ldquo;facts&rdquo;, there is another one on p.162: &ldquo;but that does not alter the fact&rdquo; etc. How afraid you must be and insecure to have to say the whole time that what you write are &ldquo;facts&rdquo; that &ldquo;show&rdquo; something, or what a bad conscience or sub-conscience.</mm> </dd></dl>
